<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The Yendes told Daily Sun they were afraid of being victimised and felt shocked that the suspect, David Ngwenya, was released without them even knowing.“As we see it, David is capable of killing and now he is back on the streets,” said Thembisile’s mum, Esther Yende.“We never knew about his release from jail because initially his bail application was turned down. “We thought the case would resume next month and that he’d spend time in jail until he appeared in court again.“But he was released on R15 000 bail and neither our defence team nor the investigating officer knew anything about it. “We want answers because we smell a rat,” said Esther.Thembisile’s brother, Mboneni, claimed the suspect was capable of getting hitmen to kill his whole family. “We believe he killed my sister and won’t think twice about harming us as well.“My sister used to complain about this man while she was still alive,” he claimed. “We want him to be jailed so that we can live in peace.” Thembisile (29) was found dead in her locked office at the East Rand power station in Springs seven months ago.This was after a two-week search for her. The cops reported that Thembisile’s decomposed body was found when Eskom employees reported a bad smell coming from the offices of the substation where she worked.